What is APR?APR stands for Annual Percentage Rate. It's a measure used to compare the yearly cost of borrowing money or earning it on savings across different products or institutions. The APR includes not only the interest rate but also any additional fees or costs associated with the transaction, providing a more comprehensive view of the total cost.

For example, if you're taking out a loan, the APR will include the interest rate plus any origination fees or other charges that are part of the loan agreement. This allows potential borrowers to compare different loans and choose the one that offers the best value for their money.

On the other hand, when it comes to savings accounts or investments, the APR represents the annualized return on your investment, again including all associated costs.

It's important to note that while APR is a useful tool for comparison, it doesn't account for compounding interest. Therefore, if you're comparing products with different types of compounding (like daily vs. monthly), you may need to use additional measures like the Annual Percentage Yield (APY) or Effective Annual Rate (EAR).yes
